Local Engagement as a Countermeasure Against Populism
PARIS – The parties that once dominated Western democracies have been shaken at their core.
Many – including in France, Italy, Greece and the United Kingdom – have suffered crushing election defeats.
Others have changed so drastically that only the name remains.
The Republican Party of US President Donald Trump has little in common with that of the former President Ronald Reagan.
These developments are similar everywhere in the West.
The leaderships of once-dominant parties swing between denial and despair, while populists fish out their traditional supporters.
Some refuse to acknowledge a legitimate reason for their defeat and dismiss their supporters of their opponents as "pitiful," as Hillary Clinton did just before she lost to Trump in 2016; others are too scared of the populist flood to launch a counter-offensive.
Neither denial nor complacency will resolve the entrenched political situation.
Progressives must reposition themselves, and this begins with a diagnosis of the inadequacies of traditional parties.
Part of the problem is that the traditional parties have failed to recognize the real issues of our time.
Still trapped on the old ideological battlefields, they ignored the declining social mobility, the intensifying environmental crises, the growing geographic inequality, the tensions regarding multiculturalism, and other issues that truly matter to voters.
Decades ago, they were the vanguard.
Today, they stand alone in the forest and wonder where everyone has gone.
Sociology could have an answer as to why the mainstream has strayed off course.
The gap between their objective analysis of reality and the policies of governments has widened into a chasm.
In most Western countries, economists have long been aware of the increasing disparity in income and other indicators between some wealthy, globalization-benefiting cities and the rest of the country.
Yet until the government of French President Emmanuel Macron implemented it, no national head of government had introduced tax cuts based on place of residence.
As a result of this policy, 1% of the French GDP is now primarily redistributed to the poorest parts of the country.
Traditional parties could also learn by directly listening to voters rather than only through the filters of media and opinion institutes.
In the year 2016, Macron's movement En Marche! launched the largest door-to-door survey in French history.
What the voters told the pollsters became the basis for Macron's presidential campaign.
For example, "La Grande Marche" had collected countless statements from women about harassment more than a year before the revelations about Harvey Weinstein's alleged sexual harassment of women, and Macron promised to address the issue if elected.
At the time, Macron's stance made him a target of jokes from his opponents; however, the laughter quickly faded with the rise of the #MeToo era.
However, a precise understanding of society alone is not sufficient.
The traditional parties also suffer from poor organization.
They have long believed that modern politics should be organized around elections, where activists distribute flyers at intervals and rally candidates.
This was less cynicism than a symptom of an approach that views democracy as a marketplace, consisting of state providers (the government) and consumers (the citizens).
According to this perspective, the sole purpose of a party is to gain and maintain power.
It is no wonder that citizens and even party members feel ignored between elections.
Despite these weaknesses, established parties had a number of advantages that delayed their collapse.
In recent years, they had a technological advantage over less established opponents, and they were the only political actors with organized voter groups that could mobilize people to elections, organize protests, and launch petitions.
But this model no longer works.
Citizens today refuse to be mere consumers of state policy.
Along with a higher level of education, new demands for participation emerged.
The voters want to be treated as political actors with their own agency and not as peasants in the game of chess of others.
Furthermore, the governments themselves are no longer the only providers of political measures.
This is one of the harsh lessons we had to learn in the two years we worked alongside Macron at the Élysée Palace.
The most important political challenges today – climate change, religious extremism, digital upheavals, and gender equality – cannot be addressed solely by national governments.
These challenges require deep cultural changes and, in most cases, measures at the sub- and supranational levels.
And finally, technology has lowered the barriers to political participation, so that traditional parties can no longer rely on the incumbent advantage and entrenched support networks.
Those who can handle Google, Twitter, and Facebook well do not need a centuries-old party apparatus.
Political movements must therefore be reorganized accordingly.
The focus should be on concrete measures and not just on elections.
The formal administrative structure of a party should serve as an administrative "back office"; the front office should be staffed by people on the ground.
We refer to this as local citizen projects at La République En Marche!.
These can range from after-school reading courses and integration programs for immigrants to cooperative vegetable gardens and digital training for seniors.
In any case, the focus is on offering solutions tailored to local problems and thus strengthening communities.
Such projects should today be considered indispensable complements to state policy.
In the future, the ability of a party to offer rewarding ways for political and civic engagement will be crucial to its attractiveness.
And by demonstrating their reform policies daily "live," the parties have already prepared the ground for success on election day.
If voters refuse to listen to what is being said, the answer is not to shout louder.
This is the hard lesson that traditional parties have learned.
Only those who demonstrate a commitment to improving people's lives, rather than simply winning elections, can attract people to their side.
Reconnecting with the concerns of voters therefore goes hand in hand with adapting party organizations.
To offer a successful alternative to populism, we need a progressive policy at the local level.
